result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (4th) and Operating w/ PAC (4th). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (4th) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (4th) was dismissed by the court.

  • Woody D Wickersheim was found guilty of OWI (4th), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Defendant may petition for early termination of probation term after completion of 18 months, provided request is joined by agent and all financial obligations are paid in full and all treatment programming is completed.
Prior to re-licensing the defendant is to complete an OWI Assessment.

miscConds.notes: Cash Bond previously posted in the amount of $1200.00 has been applied.  The remaining balance of the costs to be paid directly to the Waushara County Clerk of Court within 60 days or establish a payment plan.  Failure to pay may result in suspension of your driver's license, tax intercept, a civil judgment being entered against you, a warrant being issued for your arrest for contempt and/or the debt being turned over to a collection agency.
Same repayment provisions apply as noted above for the Fine.

The defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars other than in furtherance of obligations as to Local 139 or as an officer conducting business on behalf of the Coloma Fire Department and/or Hancock Area Vets Association, and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician.
DNA sample to be provided and surcharge assessed.  Court will specifically allow travel out of State for work related purposes.
Defendant to undergo an alcohol and other drug assessment and comply with any further counseling and/or treatment as deemed appropriate by the supervising agent.

timeConds.notes: Huber Privileges and Good Time Credit granted.  Pursuant to s. 346.65(7), Wis. Stats., Defendant shall be required to remain in the County Jail for not less than a 48 consecutive hour period prior to release for Huber.  Sentence to commence forthwith.

Case Called @ 1:25 PM: Defendant Woody D Wickersheim in court with attorney Eric Paul Pitsch.  Steven Paul Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  ADA recites resolution.  Def and counsel confirm State's recital.    Defendant advised of permissible punishment.  Def agrees w/3 prior convictions as recited by the Court.  Plea QN reviewed w/Defendant.  Plea colloquy entertained.  Collateral consequences explained. Chapter 950 compliance addressed.  Plea Ct 1 (OWI 4):  NC   Court accepts plea and enters JOC. Ct 2 dismissed outright.  All companion civil citations DRI 16TR-832, 896, 897, 898 and 899.  Argument by ADA.  Court states for the record that reference letters received from Atty Pitsch have been reviewed.  ADA admits receipt of reference letters.  Argument by Atty Pitsch - argues for lesser county jail.  Court discusses probation with Defendant.  Statement by Def: Yes.   The Court:  S/W - 2 yrs probation.  Early term of supervision at any time after completion of 18 mos; 60 days WCJ, Huber with mandatory 48 hr requirement prior to release for Huber & GT with No TS Credit, must commence sentence today, AODA and any follow thru;  the defendant must maintain absolute sobriety, may not be present upon the premises of any bars other than in furtherance of obligations as to Local 139 or as an officer conducting business on behalf of the Coloma Fire Dept and/or Hancock Area Vets Association; and is prohibited from possessing/ingesting any impairing substances that have not been prescribed by a physician; $2200 Fine plus $42.50 Blood Draw Fee - bond to be applied, 60 DTP any Bal or PP; 33 mos DL Rev/IID.  Def strongly encouraged to obtain Occ DL as soon as able due to period of DL Rev and IID order to run concurrently;  DNA Sample and Surcharge ordered by the Court.  Defendant advised of right to expunge DNA record through the Department of Justice.  JOC to specifically state that Court will allow interstate - outside the state for work related purposes.
